The set \( F \) is **not** sequentially compact because the functions \( F(x) = \int_0^x f(t) dt \) for \( f \in M \) are uniformly bounded but not necessarily equicontinuous (e.g., \( f \) could be a sequence of "spikes" with bounded height but increasing frequency). The Arzelà-Ascoli theorem (1) is the standard tool for proving sequential compactness in \( C[0,1] \), but it fails here due to the lack of equicontinuity.

\boxed{D}
